    pearls: ["TMNG is the most common cause of hyperthyroidism in elderly patients in iodine-deficient areas and the second most common cause overall after Graves disease","Unlike Graves disease, TMNG does NOT remit with antithyroid drugs — definitive treatment (RAI or surgery) is always required; methimazole is used only as bridge therapy","RAIU scan pattern distinguishes TMNG from Graves: TMNG shows patchy uptake with multiple hot nodules and suppressed surrounding tissue; Graves shows diffuse homogeneous increased uptake","Jod-Basedow phenomenon: sudden iodine excess (contrast dye, amiodarone, iodine supplements) can trigger hyperthyroidism in patients with autonomous nodular disease — warn patients about this risk","Apathetic thyrotoxicosis in the elderly: TMNG may present atypically with weight loss, weakness, depression, and atrial fibrillation without classic hyperadrenergic symptoms — check TSH in elderly patients with new-onset atrial fibrillation","Higher RAI doses (15-30 mCi) are needed for TMNG compared to Graves (10-15 mCi) because of larger gland size and lower radiosensitivity","Pre-RAI methimazole is essential in elderly and cardiac patients to prevent thyroid storm from post-treatment hormone release — but must be stopped 3-7 days before RAI to allow adequate iodine uptake"],
